template(name="expressionsPart1Theory")
  p {{_'You will use expressions in every program and programming language'}}.
  p {{_'Expression is every statement which produces value'}}:
  ul
    li <i>1 + 2</i>
    li <i>2 &lt; 5</i>
    li <i>1 &lt;&equals; 2</i>
    li ...
  p {{_'If you want to see the result of expression, you need to print it with console.log() function'}}.
  p {{_'We use classic mathematical operators in the next example'}}:
  +codeInText
    |console.log(1 + 2);
    br
    |console.log(6 - 2);
    br
    |console.log(2 * 3);
    br
    |console.log(6 / 3);
    br
    |console.log(1 &lt; 2);
    br
    |console.log(2 &gt; 3);
    br
    |console.log(2 &lt;&equals; 3);
    br
    |console.log(1 &gt;&equals; 2);
  p {{_'You can copy and paste code above into the code editor and play with it'}}.
  p {{_'Notice spaces between operators and numbers'}}. {{_'It is a good practice to leave space before and after operator'}}.
  p {{_'You can also combine operators'}}:
  +codeInText
    |console.log(1 + 2 * 3 / 2);
    br
    |console.log((6 - 2) / 4);
    br
    |console.log(1 + 3 &lt;&equals; 4);

  h2 {{_'Conventions'}}
  p {{_'Good practice is to leave space between operators'}}:
  +codeInText
    |//{{_'bad'}}
    br
    |console.log(1+2);
    br
    |console.log(1&lt;=2+5);
    br
    |console.log((6-2) / (2+2));
    br
    |//{{_'good'}}
    br
    |console.log(1 + 2);
    br
    |console.log(1 &lt;= 2 + 5);
    br
    |console.log((6 - 2) / (2 + 2));

  +conventionsNote

  p {{_'Once you understand what is going on, you can continue to exercise'}}.